  "texts": [
    "Alternatively, (2.17) could describe a \"radar\"-type experiment: in the background of a X←12 scattering event, we use a † 3 to send in a pulse of light, whose reflection is recorded at a later point with b 4.",
    "If 1 and 6 create and absorb a macroscopic object like a black hole, and 2 and 5 create and absorb a test particle moving in its background, this could very accurately measure the black hole's metric as discussed recently in [8].",
    "This is somewhat similar to probing the Solar System's metric by tracking the time it takes for light to travel to a spacecraft and back.All observables so far involve at most two factors of S and S †.",
    "Starting from 6-points, new options arise that are more radically out-of-time-order.",
    "An example isin ⟨6| b 5 a 4 b † 3 a † 2 |1⟩ in = ⟨0| b 6 b 5 a 4 b † 3 a † 2 a † 1 |0⟩ = ⟨0| a 6 a 5 S a 4 S † a † 3 S a † 2 a † 1 |0⟩, (2.18)where we used the stability condition in the first equality."
  ],
